    en: "Passing a stopped school bus with flashing red lights is one of the most serious traffic violations in New York. Vehicle and Traffic Law 1174 requires all traffic — in both directions — to stop when a school bus has its red lights flashing and the stop arm extended. A first offense carries a fine up to $400, up to 30 days in jail, and 5 points on the license. Many Monroe County districts now use school bus stop-arm cameras that issue civil penalties by mail under VTL 1174-a. A camera-based violation is civil, not criminal; it does not add points."
